  abstract =    {Abstract
Monitoring many different individual loads on customer premises is a costly, complex, and trouble-prone operation. The availability of a single instrument that could plug into the meter socket and measure individual premise loads would greatly simplify and reduce the cost of customer load monitoring. This report provides the test results of such a prototype instrument.

Background

Building upon university-level research, EPRI worked closely with Enetics, Inc. to develop and deliver in 1997 an instrument that could accurately measure individual residential loads from the meter socket. This approach minimizes the disruption to the homeowner and reduces the risk of damage to the instrumentation. Enetics successfully commercialized the instrument for the residential market. Enetics later developed an enhanced version of the instrument for use in commercial buildings with three-phase service. This program conducted beta tests of four Commercial Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring System (CNILMS) instruments at three utility host sites.

Objective

To verify that the instrument was able to accurately and repeatedly disaggregate the customer loads from the meter socket; to build a load library of readily recognizable end-use loads; to identify design deficiencies or potential enhancements prior to final development and commercial introduction.

Approach

Four test instruments were installed at host customer sites provided by three utility companies. Data from the four instruments were captured, stored locally, and regularly uploaded to a remote server for diagnosis and evaluation. To verify the accuracy of the test instruments, parallel instrumentation was installed on many of the end-use loads.

Results

The CNILMS instruments were easily and quickly installed in all cases and the instrument proved to be very reliable and accurate for measuring overall load. In several cases, the instrument was able to detect the presence of over twenty individual loads. Serious limitations were identified in the current version, however. The CNILMS units were unable to:

o Identify individual loads if they turned on or off simultaneously.

o Successfully identify and properly calculate the energy consumption of multiple identical loads.

o Combine the individual loads in "multi-state" devices such as refrigerators into one load identifiable as "refrigerator," although the individual constituent loads were often recognizable.

o Correctly calculate the energy consumption of loads with variable thermal characteristics such as refrigerators.

o Identify a load signal and correlate that signal to a named load. A trained technician must manually assign a load name to the loads identified by the instrument.

EPRI Perspective

Each of the participating host utilities and their participating customers believe that there would be a large market for a successful CNILMS instrument in deregulated energy markets. Energy service companies or energy service suppliers would use the device to help customers compare the energy performance of individual buildings or stores; compare the energy performance of equipment against nameplate ratings; identify poorly performing equipment; resolve high-bill complaints; identify new equipment installed in buildings under performance energy contracts; and optimize overall energy use. It appears that the largest market need is for an instrument that can accurately measure the "big three" commercial loads -- HVAC, refrigeration, and lighting.

Traditional methods of measuring end-use loads in such customer premises require the installation of expensive, failure-prone instrumentation. The custom installation of such instrumentation generally means that it cannot be economically moved to another site and that it is therefore difficult to economically collect data from many sites. The CNILMS approach has tremendous appeal because of its low cost, rapid installation, ability to measure many different loads, and high reliability.

Unfortunately, the current state of development of the instrument is inadequate for commercial acceptance, and considerable additional R&D is required to bring the product to a state of commercial readiness. The instrument developer has development programs underway to resolve these outstanding issues.},
